  ],
  "q1_wrong": [
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "pebble.Batch", "note": "record.Writer record/record.go:673 via 'flusher' with carrier bench.pebbleDB — the chain is nonsense (a byte sink, not a DB); I could find no injection and had to label it unconfirmed/likely false"},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "pebble.Batch", "note": "keyspan.SpanIterOptions internal/keyspan/iter.go:83 via BlockPropertyFilter carrier rangeKeyMasking — grep for the injection found nothing; shipped as unconfirmed"},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "pebble.Batch", "note": "MISSED the highest-risk retainer entirely: flushableEntry's embedded `flushable` interface (flushable.go:70) holding *flushableBatch whose data aliases Batch.data (batch.go:1974/2007). It also missed mergingIterLevel.iter (merging_iter.go:25), the base of the whole iterator-stack laundering. Both found by reading, not by Sense"},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "pebble.Batch", "note": "direct_callers list is heavily polluted — cache.shard.set, vfs.MemFS.Lock, binfmt.Formatter.String, colblk.RawBytesBuilder.Put all listed as 'calls Batch'; none touch pebble.Batch. Unusable as-is, I ignored that whole section"}
  ],
  "q2_fallbacks": [
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "pebble.Batch", "fallback": "grep", "missing": "no injection/assignment sites — retained_note explicitly says 'Which satisfier lands at runtime is unverified'. Every single row required a grep to find where the concrete value is stored (grep WriteRecord( → db.go:908/950; grep boundLimitedFilter → db.go:1377; grep 'Mask:' → db.go:1312, range_keys.go:575; grep MaybeWrapIfInvariants → db.go:1502)"},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "pebble.Batch", "fallback": "read", "missing": "no goroutine/concurrency information at all — Step 3 needed go-statements, so I grepped for 'go ' and 'runAsync' to find record/log_writer.go:595, compaction_scheduler.go:306, wal/failover_manager.go:335"},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "pebble.Batch", "fallback": "grep", "missing": "retention via slice/pointer aliasing (b.data = batch.data) is invisible to it; I found flushableBatch only by grepping 'type flushableBatch struct' after noticing newFlushableBatch in the graph's called_by list"},
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "pebble.Batch", "fallback": "read", "missing": "the 'inherits' entry metamorphic.readerCloser gave no store site, so I grepped setSnapshot( and read metamorphic/ops.go:1874 to establish it's a negative"}
  ],
  "q3_hints": [
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query_before": "sense_graph symbol=pebble.Batch", "query_after": "sense_blast symbol=pebble.Batch max_hops=4", "hint": "next_steps: '67 callers found — check blast radius before changing this symbol' — and the CLAUDE.md note about retained_via_interfaces; the blast call is what produced the interface-laundering table that anchored Step 2"},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "pebble.Batch", "query_before": "treat retained_via_interfaces rows as findings", "query_after": "grep each row for its actual construction site before stating it", "hint": "retained_note: 'carrier is a concrete satisfier of via ... Which satisfier lands at runtime is unverified' — this directly caused me to label rows confirmed vs unconfirmed instead of shipping all 14"}
  ],
  "q4_value": "retained_via_interfaces on sense_blast — it handed me 11 real interface-laundered retention points across five unrelated packages (WAL failover, compaction scheduler, range-key masking, iterv2, bench) in one call. That is exactly the class grep cannot find, because none of those struct definitions name Batch; recovering that set by hand would have meant enumerating every interface in the repo and checking satisfiers.",
  "q5_improve": "Give retained_via_interfaces the assignment site, not just the chain: for each row, the file:line where a value is actually stored into that field (the `Mask: &i.parent.rangeKeyMasking` at range_keys.go:575, the `WriteRecord(..., b)` at db.go:908). That single field would have eliminated ~8 of my 10 greps. Second: treat slice/pointer aliasing between structs (flushableBatch.data = batch.data) as a retention edge — missing that meant Sense omitted the single highest-risk row in the audit.",
  "score": 8,
  "score_rationale": "retained_via_interfaces gave me 11 confirmed cross-package retainers I could not have enumerated with grep in this session (Q1), but every one needed a grep for its injection site because the tool ships chains without assignment sites, it emitted two false rows, and it missed the top-risk flushableBatch aliasing entirely (Q2), so it accelerated rather than replaced the work."
}

